Ben

snippet.title: Ben Gibbard: Live From Home (3/26/20)
snippet.description:
Hello everyone, 

We’re heading into the home stretch of the daily shows! Thank you to everyone who’s watched, asked great questions and made requests. This has been a blast for me. 

I wanted to give you guys a heads up for the rest of the week. The schedule is as follows;

THURSDAY (TODAY)

An all request set culled from the years 2012-present. Get your requests in for songs from such albums as;

- Former Lives 
- Kintsugi
- Bandwagonesque
- Thank You For Today

Plus soundtrack cuts, singles, etc. 

Today’s show is in benefit of Your Supplies Save Lives (https://www.suppliessaveliveswa.org). Washington State health care workers are running out of safety equipment to protect themselves on the front lines of the COVID-19 outbreak. If you have any, please donate your unopened boxes of masks (N95 preferred), gowns, eye protection, and gloves to keep front-line health care workers healthy so they can save lives! All supplies will be allocated to Washington State hospitals and first responders treating COVID-19 patients. 

FRIDAY

A Top-10, all request show voted on by YOU! Vote here: https://found.ee/BenGibbard-LiveFromHome-Vote

I’ll play the resulting top-10, countdown style! 

Voting closes tonight 3/26 at 9pm PT.

SATURDAY

Dealer’s Choice. 

SUNDAY

The last of the daily shows. This will be an all-request cover show. 

See you guys soon! 

xo 

Ben

snippet.title: Ben Gibbard: Live From Home (3/18/20)
snippet.description:
Hey there everyone,

Thanks so much for tuning in yesterday. I hope it was as cathartic for you as is was for me. Please keep those requests and questions coming, I’ll be back on the virtual air at 4pm PST.

I do have a request for those who might be able to help...

Today’s show will be in benefit of the Aurora Commons (https://www.auroracommons.org). For those who are not familiar, they are a wonderful organization that provides a safe space for people temporarily experiencing homelessness on Aurora Avenue here in Seattle. 

At this point, there are no shelters available in North Seattle near The AC and only a few number of beds in neighboring hotels. The AC currently is pushing the city to allow for organized homeless encampments so that housed people don’t become afraid of folks setting up camp on their front lawns. So here’s what I’d like to ask of you...

If you are in the Seattle area OR have access to an open and safe post office/shipping location, please drop off or send any and all tents/sleeping bags (used is fine) to the following address;

The Aurora Commons c/o
Lisa Etter-Carson
927 N 89th St
Seattle, WA 98013

If you do drop off, please knock, leave your donations on the front porch, and walk away to maintain appreciate social distancing. 

Thank you,

Ben

snippet.title: Ben Gibbard: Live From Home
snippet.description:
Hey Everyone,

I know you are all really freaked out right now.  I am too.  And while I’m proud that we’re all doing the necessary things at the moment to help flatten the curve, I know it has left us all incredibly isolated.  

But because we’re all going through this nightmare together we are quite literally NOT alone. Our lives and stories are all linked, maybe more now than they have ever been.  

Be it with DCFC, Postal Service, or solo I have always been grateful for the honor you have bestowed upon us by choosing to congregate en masse around our music.  Some of you have traveled great distances and/or shelled out large sums of money to see us play and that has never been lost on me.  So in this crazy and unprecedented time, I’d like to return the favor by coming to YOU.

For the next few weeks I will be playing songs everyday from my home studio.  We will be streaming on YouTube at 4pm PST daily.  We’re still working out the details but I’m hoping to take some requests and maybe even have a guest or two stop by digitally.  The first show will be tomorrow.  It will assuredly be a little wonky and glitchy but we’re gonna do our best.

See You Tomorrow.

xo

Ben

snippet.textDisplay: Because I’m disabled and I can’t drive, I’ve never been able to pick up and leave the house whenever I want to. However, I always look forward to getting out of the house for work and a couple of weekly outings.  Now of course, my time out of the house has fallen to zero.  These shows have meant so much to me as something to look forward to. I will never be able to put it into words.  Years from now,  when I’m telling people what it was like to live through this, I hope I remember to mention you. I hope I tell people that you really seemed to understand that music can help people through difficult times.

snippet.textDisplay: 20 years ago I fell in love with a boy. We shared your music back and forth in a time I now call our youth. 40 years old now and he is in Seattle - I am still in our home town. I hadn't listened to your music in a long time bc it just HURT. We are close but never amounted to a happily ever after- friendship though sometimes has to be more valuable. Anyway he sent me the link to the 3/24 show - then called telling me that the playlist was our youth. Thank you. It seems so small I am sure.. but the fact that I remind him - that the music didn't only remind me of him.. it was a 2 way street. Be well.

snippet.textDisplay: Thanks so much for playing the only living boy in NY. I got my first tattoo when I was 19 or 20 on my arm of a storm cloud with a sun coming behind it. Loved the sentiment of getting all of your  news from the weather report. I took that to mean that you should block out everything besides how the day is going to be and go from there. I also put the sun behind the storm to remind myself that behind every storm is a blanket of sunshine. For someone who suffers from anxiety and depression that song and sentiment means so much to me, knowing what Paul was going through while writing it. I was so amazed and glad to hear Ben perform it today, especially as there is so much craziness going on. Important to just look at the weather and tune out all the nonsense. :) thanks for keeping us not just sane but truly happy and at peace every night for the last two weeks Ben!

snippet.textDisplay: I'm not sure if Ben reads these or not but would love to hear "You Are a Tourist".  2011 was a time the economy was slowly coming back and it hit my profession in Architecture really hard.  I was out of college 2 years prior and took a job not in my profession and back in my home town.   When codes and keys was released,  you are a tourist really struck home with me and my current life situation.   The song helped me move on from the job and took a pay cut to leave town and back into architecture.  Thanks Death Cab for your inspirational lyrics.

snippet.textDisplay: I wanted you to know that "What Sarah Said" is very impactful to me. I LOVE the song but I simply cannot listen to it. It asks an important question but it's one I don't want to think about. But more than that, the way the song was arranged, performed and recorded was perfection IMO. Once I was able to actually absorb the song it hit me pretty hard. In short, I was changed because of that song and I thank you for it. Summer Skin is gorgeous too.

snippet.textDisplay: Ben: how’s the running going? As an ultra runner, I’m overwhelmed with all my races canceled, on top of my restaurant closing— so all of these “concerts” every day are great— thanks. Some more ideas: all the runners seem to love Lord Huron’s “Time to run” (which my wife says has cowbells) — it’s right up your alley— of course, I would love “Born to run” which is kinda in your wheel house, and last but not least for something completely different, how about some Talking Heads, like “Once I’m a lifetime” because let’s all hope this only happens to us all ONCE. Thanks man.

snippet.textDisplay: Hey Ben, your music makes me feel EXTREMELY nostalgic, as it was DCFC's albums that always accompanied my formative teenage years. Tiny Vessels remind me of my first girlfriend, she was very life changing for me. She showed me love and also pain, and these are the emotions that flood my brain when I listen to the song that I was obsessed with at the time, (Tiny Vessels). The bittersweet memories that accompany the perfectly paralleled lyrics are the most vivid I have of them younger years. I would be so honoured if you were to play this when you next grace us with a livestream.

snippet.textDisplay: I woke up in the middle of the night a few weeks ago with Your New Twin Sized Bed stuck in my head, so I put on Narrow Stairs and had the best cry I’ve had in a while. I felt like I had a boulder lifted off me. It was awesome to see you perform it today, I haven’t been lucky enough to see DCFC live yet. I fell in love with your music at like 10 and I’m 22 now. Growing up has only given me more life experiences to connect with these songs. It’s awesome that you’re doing this— and you’re making an effort to help out organizations in Seattle and talk about the bands you’ve toured with and love! Thanks for these livestreams.

snippet.textDisplay: This is becoming the thing I look forward to coming home from work for every night.  Thank you SO MUCH..wow, what a privilege to get to just hang out with you like this. Saw you performing songs by yourself live and couldn't believe it. This was a gift and I thank you ever so much. Truly feel blessed, and want you to know Your music has been getting me through some hard times these days.
Keep on keeping on🙏

snippet.textDisplay:
Thank you so much for your thoughtfulness. 

As everyone knows, it's a strange time, and it was incredible to have the intention to revisit your tiny desk session, and find this. Not only one of my favorite artists, but another human reaching out and connecting with the world, when we are all feeling a different kind of isolation than we've ever felt before. 

Thank you, so so much. 

If I may, I would love to hear a Time Forgot - Connor Oberst cover.

snippet.textDisplay: Your talent is so raw and amazing.  I've been listening to your music ever since I have been in middle school and I don't know what I would do without it- It's been my inspiration and my rock. I'm currently quarantining at home with a fever and sore throat after exposure to the coronavirus last week while working in the ER, and now your music is one of the only things keeping me going as I sit at home.  Seeing you in concert in Chicago when you performed all of Transatlantacism was incredible and now seeing that you have been going live doing this is incredible and means so much to so many people ❤ Thank you, and I am glad you are safe and have recovered!

DCFC has been one of my favorite bands for 15 years but I hadn’t really been listening to them much lately. I broke up with my gf of 4 years about a month ago and so ben’s lyrics and melodies were exactly what I needed. I’ve had tiny vessels on a loop in my mind for weeks. And now today here you are helping everyone through an even harder time for the country.

Thank you Ben.
